I've tried personally to optimize it... (rgb2hsl, I didn't do the other one...)

```
vec3 rgb2hsl_v2( in vec3 c ) {
    float h = 0.0;
    float s = 0.0;
    float l = 0.0;
    
    float r = clamp(c.r, 0.0, 1.0);
    float g = clamp(c.g, 0.0, 1.0);
    float b = clamp(c.b, 0.0, 1.0);

    float cMin = min( r, min( g, b ) );
    float cMax = max( r, max( g, b ) );

    l = ( cMax + cMin ) / 2.0;
    
    if ( cMax > cMin ) {
	float cDelta = cMax - cMin;
        
        //s = l < .05 ? cDelta / ( cMax + cMin ) : cDelta / ( 2.0 - ( cMax + cMin ) ); //Original
        //s = l < .0 ? cDelta / ( cMax + cMin ) : cDelta / ( 2.0 - ( cMax + cMin ) );
        // l can't be under 0.0...
	s = cDelta / ( 2.0 - ( cMax + cMin ) );
        
        float rg = float(r == cMax) * (g - b) / cDelta;
        float gb = float(g == cMax) * (2.0 + (b - r) / cDelta);
        float br = float(b == cMax) * (4.0 + (r - g) / cDelta);
        
        h = rg + gb + br;
        
	h += step(h, 0.0) * 6.0;
	h = h / 6.0;
    }
    
	return vec3( h, s, l );
}
```

I've kept the first huge if, because it probably is more performant to exit out early of all those calculations, instead of always calculating them.

Also quick question, is float(bool == bool) considered branching? No, right?

Anyways, the color conversion still works like the original function.
Test it out! https://www.shadertoy.com/view/msVfzG
hsl2rgb_v2() is the new version, hsl2rgb() is the old one...

